{"editor_item_1": "<div>\n                                                    <div class=\"ka-block\"\n                                                        style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.25rem; font-size: 14.4px;\">\n                                                        <div class=\"ka-title\"\n                                                            style=\"margin: 0px 0px 0.5rem; padding: 0px 0px 0.25rem; font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 800; text-transform: uppercase; color: rgb(37, 99, 235); border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(226, 232, 240);\">\n                                                            A. Foundation &amp; Introduction</div>\n                                                        <div>Gross Domestic Product (GDP) acts as the primary scorecard\n                                                            of a nation's economic health, representing the total\n                                                            monetary value of all final goods and services produced\n                                                            within a country's borders in a specific time period.</div>\n                                                    </div>\n                                                    <div class=\"ka-block\"\n                                                        style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.25rem; font-size: 14.4px;\">\n                                                        <div class=\"ka-title\"\n                                                            style=\"margin: 0px 0px 0.5rem; padding: 0px 0px 0.25rem; font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 800; text-transform: uppercase; color: rgb(37, 99, 235); border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(226, 232, 240);\">\n                                                            B. Definitions of Terms</div>\n                                                        <div>\n                                                            <ul>\n                                                                <li><b>Nominal GDP:</b> Economic output evaluated at\n                                                                    current market prices, unadjusted for inflation.\n                                                                </li>\n                                                                <li><b>Real GDP:</b> Output adjusted for price changes\n                                                                    (inflation/deflation), reflecting true growth.</li>\n                                                                <li><b>GDP Deflator:</b> A measure of the level of\n                                                                    prices of all new, domestically produced, final\n                                                                    goods and services.</li>\n                                                            </ul>\n                                                        </div>\n                                                    </div>\n                                                    <div class=\"ka-block\"\n                                                        style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.25rem; font-size: 14.4px;\">\n                                                        <div class=\"ka-title\"\n                                                            style=\"margin: 0px 0px 0.5rem; padding: 0px 0px 0.25rem; font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 800; text-transform: uppercase; color: rgb(37, 99, 235); border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(226, 232, 240);\">\n                                                            C. Flow Chart / Mind Map Overview</div>\n                                                        <div><b>\ud83e\udde0 MindMap Overview:</b><br>[Output Method (Agriculture,\n                                                            Industry, Services)] \u279c [Income Method (Wages, Rent,\n                                                            Interest, Profit)] \u279c [Expenditure Method (C + I + G + NX)] \u279c\n                                                            <b>National GDP</b>\n                                                        </div>\n                                                    </div>\n                                                    <div class=\"ka-block\"\n                                                        style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.25rem; font-size: 14.4px;\">\n                                                        <div class=\"ka-title\"\n                                                            style=\"margin: 0px 0px 0.5rem; padding: 0px 0px 0.25rem; font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 800; text-transform: uppercase; color: rgb(37, 99, 235); border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(226, 232, 240);\">\n                                                            D. History &amp; Development</div>\n                                                        <div>Developed by Simon Kuznets in the 1930s to help the US\n                                                            government understand the Great Depression, GDP was adopted\n                                                            globally post-Bretton Woods (1944). In Nepal, systematic\n                                                            national accounting began in the 1960s with the\n                                                            establishment of the Central Bureau of Statistics (now NSO).\n                                                        </div>\n                                                    </div>\n                                                    <div class=\"ka-block\"\n                                                        style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.25rem; font-size: 14.4px;\">\n                                                        <div class=\"ka-title\"\n                                                            style=\"margin: 0px 0px 0.5rem; padding: 0px 0px 0.25rem; font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 800; text-transform: uppercase; color: rgb(37, 99, 235); border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(226, 232, 240);\">\n                                                            E. Objective, Need &amp; Significance</div>\n                                                        <div>To quantify the absolute size of the economy, determine the\n                                                            trajectory of growth, and formulate foundational monetary\n                                                            and fiscal policies.</div>\n                                                    </div>\n                                                    <div class=\"ka-block\"\n                                                        style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.25rem; font-size: 14.4px;\">\n                                                        <div class=\"ka-title\"\n                                                            style=\"margin: 0px 0px 0.5rem; padding: 0px 0px 0.25rem; font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 800; text-transform: uppercase; color: rgb(37, 99, 235); border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(226, 232, 240);\">\n                                                            F. Core Content (25-Mark Depth)</div>\n                                                        <div><b>The Core Construct:</b> Nepal primarily relies on the\n                                                            Value Added (Production) approach for structural compilation\n                                                            due to data constraints in the expenditure model. The\n                                                            economy is bifurcated into 18 ISIC economic activities. A\n                                                            critical shift in understanding Nepal's GDP is its heavy\n                                                            reliance on the tertiary (service) sector, which contributes\n                                                            over 60%, while agriculture contributes roughly 24% despite\n                                                            employing a vast majority. The challenge is the 'informal\n                                                            economy' paradox, which operates outside the recorded GDP\n                                                            metric but drives real-world consumption.</div>\n                                                    </div>\n                                                    <div class=\"ka-block\"\n                                                        style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.25rem; font-size: 14.4px;\">\n                                                        <div class=\"ka-title\"\n                                                            style=\"margin: 0px 0px 0.5rem; padding: 0px 0px 0.25rem; font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 800; text-transform: uppercase; color: rgb(37, 99, 235); border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(226, 232, 240);\">\n                                                            G. Calculation / Derivation Structure</div>\n                                                        <div><b>Derivation (Expenditure Approach):</b><br><span\n                                                                class=\"ka-math\"\n                                                                style=\"padding: 0.2rem 0.4rem; font-family: monospace; background: none 0% 0% / auto repeat scroll padding-box border-box rgb(248, 250, 252); border-radius: 4px;\">Y\n                                                                = C + I + G + (X - M)</span><br>Where <i>C</i> =\n                                                            Consumption, <i>I</i> = Investment, <i>G</i> = Gov\n                                                            Expenditure, <i>X</i> = Exports, <i>M</i> = Imports. In\n                                                            Nepal, <i>(X - M)</i> represents a massive deficit gap.\n                                                        </div>\n                                                    </div>\n                                                    <div class=\"ka-block\"\n                                                        style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.25rem; font-size: 14.4px;\">\n                                                        <div class=\"ka-title\"\n                                                            style=\"margin: 0px 0px 0.5rem; padding: 0px 0px 0.25rem; font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 800; text-transform: uppercase; color: rgb(37, 99, 235); border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(226, 232, 240);\">\n                                                            H. Positive &amp; Negative Aspects</div>\n                                                        <div><span class=\"ka-highlight-green\"\n                                                                style=\"color: rgb(16, 185, 129); font-weight: 600;\">Strong\n                                                                Aspect:</span> Provides a globally standardized baseline\n                                                            for IMF/WB evaluations and sovereign ratings.<br><span\n                                                                class=\"ka-highlight-red\"\n                                                                style=\"color: rgb(239, 68, 68); font-weight: 600;\">Weakness:</span>\n                                                            Ignores non-market transactions (household work),\n                                                            environmental degradation, and crucially for Nepal, <span\n                                                                class=\"ka-highlight-red\"\n                                                                style=\"color: rgb(239, 68, 68); font-weight: 600;\">Remittance\n                                                                is NOT included in GDP</span>.</div>\n                                                    </div>\n                                                    <div class=\"ka-block\"\n                                                        style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.25rem; font-size: 14.4px;\">\n                                                        <div class=\"ka-title\"\n                                                            style=\"margin: 0px 0px 0.5rem; padding: 0px 0px 0.25rem; font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 800; text-transform: uppercase; color: rgb(37, 99, 235); border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(226, 232, 240);\">\n                                                            I. Recent Developments &amp; Contemporary Issues</div>\n                                                        <div>Rebasing of the National Accounts base year to 2010/11 by\n                                                            the National Statistics Office (NSO), capturing newer\n                                                            digital economy segments and better categorization of the\n                                                            service sector.</div>\n                                                    </div>\n                                                    <div class=\"ka-block\"\n                                                        style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.25rem; font-size: 14.4px;\">\n                                                        <div class=\"ka-title\"\n                                                            style=\"margin: 0px 0px 0.5rem; padding: 0px 0px 0.25rem; font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 800; text-transform: uppercase; color: rgb(37, 99, 235); border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(226, 232, 240);\">\n                                                            J. Relation to Banking Sector (National/International)</div>\n                                                        <div><b>Banking Nexus:</b> Nominal GDP directly anchors credit\n                                                            expansion limits. A standard prudential rule is that broad\n                                                            money (M2) and credit growth should align with Nominal GDP\n                                                            growth to prevent systemic asset bubbles. NRB uses projected\n                                                            GDP to calibrate the Statutory Liquidity Ratio (SLR) and\n                                                            Cash Reserve Ratio (CRR).</div>\n                                                    </div>\n                                                    <div class=\"ka-block\"\n                                                        style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.25rem; font-size: 14.4px;\">\n                                                        <div class=\"ka-title\"\n                                                            style=\"margin: 0px 0px 0.5rem; padding: 0px 0px 0.25rem; font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 800; text-transform: uppercase; color: rgb(37, 99, 235); border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(226, 232, 240);\">\n                                                            K. Real World Example / Story</div>\n                                                        <div>\n                                                            <div class=\"ka-quote\"\n                                                                style=\"padding: 0.75rem 1rem; border-left: 4px solid rgb(245, 158, 11); font-style: italic; color: rgb(71, 85, 105); background-color: rgb(248, 250, 252); border-radius: 0px 4px 4px 0px;\">\n                                                                <b>The Remittance Paradox:</b> Bikash, consider a family\n                                                                in Jhapa receiving Rs. 50,000 from Qatar. This money is\n                                                                deposited in NBL, creating banking liquidity. The family\n                                                                buys imported Indian electronics. <b>Result:</b> GDP\n                                                                does not increase (remittance is a transfer, imports\n                                                                reduce net exports). Yet, banking deposits swell and\n                                                                consumption rises. This disconnect is why GDP alone\n                                                                fails to capture Nepal's actual banking liquidity cycle.\n                                                            </div>\n                                                        </div>\n                                                    </div>\n                                                    <div class=\"ka-block\"\n                                                        style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.25rem; font-size: 14.4px;\">\n                                                        <div class=\"ka-title\"\n                                                            style=\"margin: 0px 0px 0.5rem; padding: 0px 0px 0.25rem; font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 800; text-transform: uppercase; color: rgb(37, 99, 235); border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(226, 232, 240);\">\n                                                            L. Quantitative Data (NRB, MOF, WB)</div>\n                                                        <div class=\"ka-highlight-green\"\n                                                            style=\"color: rgb(16, 185, 129); font-weight: 600;\"><b>Nepal\n                                                                GDP (2023/24 Est):</b> Rs. 5.70 Trillion. <b>Targeted\n                                                                Growth:</b> 6.0% (Monetary Policy 2080/81). <b>Inflation\n                                                                Target:</b> 6.5%. (Source: MOF/NRB).</div>\n                                                    </div>\n                                                    <div class=\"ka-block\"\n                                                        style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.25rem; font-size: 14.4px;\">\n                                                        <div class=\"ka-title\"\n                                                            style=\"margin: 0px 0px 0.5rem; padding: 0px 0px 0.25rem; font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 800; text-transform: uppercase; color: rgb(37, 99, 235); border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(226, 232, 240);\">\n                                                            M. Policy, Act, Directives &amp; Regulatory Provisions</div>\n                                                        <div><b>Regulatory Anchor:</b> Nepal Rastra Bank Act, 2058\n                                                            (Section 4) mandates the NRB to formulate monetary policy\n                                                            that sustains macroeconomic stability to support the\n                                                            Government's GDP growth targets.</div>\n                                                    </div>\n                                                    <div class=\"ka-block\"\n                                                        style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.25rem; font-size: 14.4px;\">\n                                                        <div class=\"ka-title\"\n                                                            style=\"margin: 0px 0px 0.5rem; padding: 0px 0px 0.25rem; font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 800; text-transform: uppercase; color: rgb(37, 99, 235); border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(226, 232, 240);\">\n                                                            N. Current Situation &amp; Problems in Banking</div>\n                                                        <div class=\"ka-highlight-red\"\n                                                            style=\"color: rgb(239, 68, 68); font-weight: 600;\">1.\n                                                            <b>High Credit-to-GDP Ratio:</b> Nepal's private sector\n                                                            credit-to-GDP exceeds 90%, yet economic growth is stagnant\n                                                            (low credit productivity).<br>2. <b>Informal Sector\n                                                                Leakage:</b> An estimated 35-40% of the economy is\n                                                            unbanked/shadow, skewing GDP accuracy.\n                                                        </div>\n                                                    </div>\n                                                    <div class=\"ka-block\"\n                                                        style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.25rem; padding: 1rem; font-size: 14.4px; background: rgba(37, 99, 235, 0.05); border-left: 4px solid rgb(37, 99, 235);\">\n                                                        <div class=\"ka-title\"\n                                                            style=\"margin: 0px 0px 0.5rem; padding: 0px 0px 0.25rem; font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 800; text-transform: uppercase; color: rgb(37, 99, 235); border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(226, 232, 240);\">\n                                                            O. Nepal Bank Limited (NBL) Strategy &amp; Implementation\n                                                        </div>\n                                                        <div><b>NBL Strategic Adoption (Level 9 Directive):</b> Nepal\n                                                            Bank Limited must integrate MOF's GDP sectoral growth\n                                                            targets directly into the Annual Credit Policy. By aligning\n                                                            lending portfolios toward high-GDP-contributing sectors\n                                                            (like Energy and Tourism) while rigorously enforcing NFRS 9\n                                                            Expected Credit Loss (ECL) modeling\u2014using macro-variables\n                                                            like GDP growth as forward-looking indicators\u2014NBL can\n                                                            optimize risk-weighted assets. Furthermore, strictly\n                                                            adhering to the 1% Pass Loan Loss Provisioning (Directive\n                                                            2/2082) ensures capital buffer integrity against\n                                                            macroeconomic shocks.</div>\n                                                    </div>\n                                                </div>", "editor_item_3": "<div>\n                                                    <div class=\"ka-block\"\n                                                        style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.25rem; color: rgb(15, 23, 42); font-size: 14.4px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">\n                                                        <div class=\"ka-title\"\n                                                            style=\"margin: 0px 0px 0.5rem; padding: 0px 0px 0.25rem; font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 800; text-transform: uppercase; color: rgb(37, 99, 235); border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(226, 232, 240);\">\n                                                            A. Foundation &amp; Introduction</div>\n                                                        <div>Gross Domestic Product (GDP) acts as the primary scorecard\n                                                            of a nation's economic health, representing the total\n                                                            monetary value of all final goods and services produced\n                                                            within a country's borders in a specific time period.</div>\n                                                    </div>\n                                                    <div class=\"ka-block\"\n                                                        style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.25rem; color: rgb(15, 23, 42); font-size: 14.4px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">\n                                                        <div class=\"ka-title\"\n                                                            style=\"margin: 0px 0px 0.5rem; padding: 0px 0px 0.25rem; font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 800; text-transform: uppercase; color: rgb(37, 99, 235); border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(226, 232, 240);\">\n                                                            B. Definitions of Terms</div>\n                                                        <div>\n                                                            <ul>\n                                                                <li><b>Nominal GDP:</b> Economic output evaluated at\n                                                                    current market prices, unadjusted for inflation.\n                                                                </li>\n                                                                <li><b>Real GDP:</b> Output adjusted for price changes\n                                                                    (inflation/deflation), reflecting true growth.</li>\n                                                                <li><b>GDP Deflator:</b> A measure of the level of\n                                                                    prices of all new, domestically produced, final\n                                                                    goods and services.</li>\n                                                            </ul>\n                                                        </div>\n                                                    </div>\n                                                    <div class=\"ka-block\"\n                                                        style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.25rem; color: rgb(15, 23, 42); font-size: 14.4px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">\n                                                        <div class=\"ka-title\"\n                                                            style=\"margin: 0px 0px 0.5rem; padding: 0px 0px 0.25rem; font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 800; text-transform: uppercase; color: rgb(37, 99, 235); border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(226, 232, 240);\">\n                                                            C. Flow Chart / Mind Map Overview</div>\n                                                        <div><b>\ud83e\udde0 MindMap Overview:</b><br>[Output Method (Agriculture,\n                                                            Industry, Services)] \u279c [Income Method (Wages, Rent,\n                                                            Interest, Profit)] \u279c [Expenditure Method (C + I + G + NX)] \u279c\n                                                            <b>National GDP</b>\n                                                        </div>\n                                                    </div>\n                                                    <div class=\"ka-block\"\n                                                        style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.25rem; color: rgb(15, 23, 42); font-size: 14.4px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">\n                                                        <div class=\"ka-title\"\n                                                            style=\"margin: 0px 0px 0.5rem; padding: 0px 0px 0.25rem; font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 800; text-transform: uppercase; color: rgb(37, 99, 235); border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(226, 232, 240);\">\n                                                            D. History &amp; Development</div>\n                                            