                            I. Recent Developments &amp; Contemporary Issues</div>\n                                                        <div>Rebasing of the National Accounts base year to 2010/11 by\n                                                            the National Statistics Office (NSO), capturing newer\n                                                            digital economy segments and better categorization of the\n                                                            service sector.</div>\n                                                    </div>\n                                                    <div class=\"ka-block\"\n                                                        style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.25rem; color: rgb(15, 23, 42); font-size: 14.4px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">\n                                                        <div class=\"ka-title\"\n                                                            style=\"margin: 0px 0px 0.5rem; padding: 0px 0px 0.25rem; font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 800; text-transform: uppercase; color: rgb(37, 99, 235); border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(226, 232, 240);\">\n                                                            J. Relation to Banking Sector (National/International)</div>\n                                                        <div><b>Banking Nexus:</b> Nominal GDP directly anchors credit\n                                                            expansion limits. A standard prudential rule is that broad\n                                                            money (M2) and credit growth should align with Nominal GDP\n                                                            growth to prevent systemic asset bubbles. NRB uses projected\n                                                            GDP to calibrate the Statutory Liquidity Ratio (SLR) and\n                                                            Cash Reserve Ratio (CRR).</div>\n                                                    </div>\n                                                    <div class=\"ka-block\"\n                                                        style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.25rem; color: rgb(15, 23, 42); font-size: 14.4px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">\n                                                        <div class=\"ka-title\"\n                                                            style=\"margin: 0px 0px 0.5rem; padding: 0px 0px 0.25rem; font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 800; text-transform: uppercase; color: rgb(37, 99, 235); border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(226, 232, 240);\">\n                                                            K. Real World Example / Story</div>\n                                                        <div>\n                                                            <div class=\"ka-quote\"\n                                                                style=\"padding: 0.75rem 1rem; border-left: 4px solid rgb(245, 158, 11); font-style: italic; color: rgb(71, 85, 105); background-color: rgb(248, 250, 252); border-radius: 0px 4px 4px 0px;\">\n                                                                <b>The Remittance Paradox:</b> Bikash, consider a family\n                                                                in Jhapa receiving Rs. 50,000 from Qatar. This money is\n                                                                deposited in NBL, creating banking liquidity. The family\n                                                                buys imported Indian electronics. <b>Result:</b> GDP\n                                                                does not increase (remittance is a transfer, imports\n                                                                reduce net exports). Yet, banking deposits swell and\n                                                                consumption rises. This disconnect is why GDP alone\n                                                                fails to capture Nepal's actual banking liquidity cycle.\n                                                            </div>\n                                                        </div>\n                                                    </div>\n                                                    <div class=\"ka-block\"\n                                                        style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.25rem; color: rgb(15, 23, 42); font-size: 14.4px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">\n                                                        <div class=\"ka-title\"\n                                                            style=\"margin: 0px 0px 0.5rem; padding: 0px 0px 0.25rem; font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 800; text-transform: uppercase; color: rgb(37, 99, 235); border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(226, 232, 240);\">\n                                                            L. Quantitative Data (NRB, MOF, WB)</div>\n                                                        <div class=\"ka-highlight-green\"\n                                                            style=\"color: rgb(16, 185, 129); font-weight: 600;\"><b>Nepal\n                                                                GDP (2023/24 Est):</b> Rs. 5.70 Trillion. <b>Targeted\n                                                                Growth:</b> 6.0% (Monetary Policy 2080/81). <b>Inflation\n                                                                Target:</b> 6.5%. (Source: MOF/NRB).</div>\n                                                    </div>\n                                                    <div class=\"ka-block\"\n                                                        style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.25rem; color: rgb(15, 23, 42); font-size: 14.4px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">\n                                                        <div class=\"ka-title\"\n                                                            style=\"margin: 0px 0px 0.5rem; padding: 0px 0px 0.25rem; font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 800; text-transform: uppercase; color: rgb(37, 99, 235); border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(226, 232, 240);\">\n                                                            M. Policy, Act, Directives &amp; Regulatory Provisions</div>\n                                                        <div><b>Regulatory Anchor:</b> Nepal Rastra Bank Act, 2058\n                                                            (Section 4) mandates the NRB to formulate monetary policy\n                                                            that sustains macroeconomic stability to support the\n                                                            Government's GDP growth targets.</div>\n                                                    </div>\n                                                    <div class=\"ka-block\"\n                                                        style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.25rem; color: rgb(15, 23, 42); font-size: 14.4px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">\n                                                        <div class=\"ka-title\"\n                                                            style=\"margin: 0px 0px 0.5rem; padding: 0px 0px 0.25rem; font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 800; text-transform: uppercase; color: rgb(37, 99, 235); border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(226, 232, 240);\">\n                                                            N. Current Situation &amp; Problems in Banking</div>\n                                                        <div class=\"ka-highlight-red\"\n                                                            style=\"color: rgb(239, 68, 68); font-weight: 600;\">1.\n                                                            <b>High Credit-to-GDP Ratio:</b> Nepal's private sector\n                                                            credit-to-GDP exceeds 90%, yet economic growth is stagnant\n                                                            (low credit productivity).<br>2. <b>Informal Sector\n                                                                Leakage:</b> An estimated 35-40% of the economy is\n                                                            unbanked/shadow, skewing GDP accuracy.\n                                                        </div>\n                                                    </div>\n                                                    <div class=\"ka-block\"\n                                                        style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.25rem; padding: 1rem; color: rgb(15, 23, 42); font-size: 14.4px; background: rgba(37, 99, 235, 0.05); border-left: 4px solid rgb(37, 99, 235);\">\n                                                        <div class=\"ka-title\"\n                                                            style=\"margin: 0px 0px 0.5rem; padding: 0px 0px 0.25rem; font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 800; text-transform: uppercase; color: rgb(37, 99, 235); border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(226, 232, 240);\">\n                                                            O. Nepal Bank Limited (NBL) Strategy &amp; Implementation\n                                                        </div>\n                                                        <div><b>NBL Strategic Adoption (Level 9 Directive):</b> Nepal\n                                                            Bank Limited must integrate MOF's GDP sectoral growth\n                                                            targets directly into the Annual Credit Policy. By aligning\n                                                            lending portfolios toward high-GDP-contributing sectors\n                                                            (like Energy and Tourism) while rigorously enforcing NFRS 9\n                                                            Expected Credit Loss (ECL) modeling\u2014using macro-variables\n                                                            like GDP growth as forward-looking indicators\u2014NBL can\n                                                            optimize risk-weighted assets. Furthermore, strictly\n                                                            adhering to the 1% Pass Loan Loss Provisioning (Directive\n                                                            2/2082) ensures capital buffer integrity against\n                                                            macroeconomic shocks.</div>\n                                                    </div>\n                                                </div>"}